GIT ARCHITECTURE & INTERNALS 

    GIT IS NOT JUST A FILE TRACKER
        - git tracks snapshots  not diffs, everytime you do a commit like a change, git takes snapshot of what the files look like at that point in time not just what changed
        this means if you change one line it snapshots a full new version of that file.
        - Git uses a key value store (SHA-1 hash) these long string that uniqule represent content of a file , no 2 diferent file conetnt will have the same hash .
        - a commit in git is a pointer to a full snapshot of your project not just the changes but the state of the whole repo right then.
        - Files are stored as objects (blobs, trees), these are essentailly blobs for file contents and trees for directories.
        git is content addressed not file name based meaning it doesnt care what the file name is called, if the content changes the hash changes, if the cintents the same git reuses the same object 
        - git is not just a tracker its a smart compressed hash based snap shot engine.

    GIT terminology & key concepts (light primer)
        - [repositpory] is a git project, a folder being tracked by git ( if it has . git directory inside it its a repo )
        - [commit] is a snap shot of your files which includes the author , timestamp, message, parent commit, etc
        - [branch] is a moveable pointer to a commit, you usally work on a main/ master branch as a dev and you have other feature branches like features as login feed, many other branches names you come across.
        - [remote] is a refs to the external copy of your repo kept usally kept online in github/gitlab smetimes called origin.
        - [staging] area also called the index is a buffer between your working directory and the repo you plan to commit.
        - [blobs] stands for binary large objects which stores the actually contents of the file
        - [trees] link file paths to blobs and other trees  which basically represent directorys and structure
        - [refs] stands for referencaes and include branches tags and some special pointers like HEAD 
        - [HEAD] is a pointer to where you currently arte the branch/ commit you are currently on
        - [Index] the actual binary file on disc that store the actual binary data which ios used by git to prep yopur commit.
        - [Object store] which is .git/object/ directory and this is where git stores all. blobs, trees and commit by SHA hash  
        - [tag] a refs to a specfic commit often used for marking releases.

    THE .git DIRECTORY
        -  every git repo has a secert folder called .git, which is also refered to as the brain of the project and conatians everything git need to function with history, config , brancvhes and more
        - [.git/refs/] is where git stores branches and tags
        - [.git/objects/] is also called the object store its where git keeps every commit ,blob and trees all compressed and  aand stored by shahash 
        - [.git/config] these are the repo specific settings meaning if you goit diffenrent remotes or user info for this project , theyll usallly go here.
        - [.git/HEAD] tells git what branch / commit you are currently on.
        - [.git/index] this is the staging area, which acts a temporary zone between editing your files and commiting them, git also build your next snapshot here 
